MissionCommands.Message: {{capsuleName}}, this is Mission Control. Prepare the cockpit for launch.
Roger. All right {{profileName}}, this is the real deal. Let's get this spacecraft ready for launch.
We will go through the launch preparation checklist. I will set the switches on my side, and you will focus on those on your side. I will guide us through, so follow my lead.
You can access the Mission Pad to read about the mission by pressing [M] on the keyboard. I will give you 30 seconds to go through the details and briefing.
To view a checklist, open the Mission Pad, click the CHECKLISTS tab and select the PRE-FLIGHT (T-5) checklist.
Let's start with the Electrical Power System, following the PRE-FLIGHT checklist.
MAIN BATTERY 1 to ON.
MAIN BATTERY 2 to ON.
MAIN BATTERY 3 to ON.
MAIN BATTERY 4 to ON.
SQUIB BATTERY 1 to ON.
SQUIB BATTERY 2 to ON.
SQUIB BATTERY 3 to ON.
Then the Fuel Cells on the main PILOT'S PANEL. Set Fuel Cell stack 1A to ON.
Fuel Cell stack 1B to ON.
Fuel Cell stack 1C to ON.
Fuel Cell stack 2A to ON.
Fuel Cell stack 2B to ON.
Fuel Cell stack 2C to ON.
In SECTION 1, set the Fuel Cell 1 POWER to ON.
And then in SECTION 2, set Fuel Cell 2 POWER to ON.
Set the COMPUTER Power to ON.
Set the MDIU (Manual Data Insertion Unit / Computer Display and Keyboard) to ON. The computer will run through some self-checks, this usually takes 20 seconds.
When the self-checks are complete (registers on the MDIU has stopped), start the COMPUTER by pressing START.
I will do my side. ARMing BOOST-INSERT Squibs.
ARMing RETRO ROCKET SQUIB 1
ARMing RETRO ROCKET SQUIB 2
ARMing RETRO ROCKET SQUIB 3
ARMing RETRO ROCKET SQUIB 4
Ok, electrical system and squibs are now set up. The last part of the checklist is mostly around the Environmental Control System.
We are going to use the built-in checklist feature to perform the last steps.
Open the [M]ission Pad again, go to CHECKLISTS, and select the PRE-FLIGHT checklist.
When RUNNING a checklist, the in-game checklist guidance system will help you execute a step. The step will automatically proceed when you set the mentioned switch to its correct position.

Some steps in a checklist that is currently running are "MANUAL" or "VERIFY" steps. When the checklist system stops at a step like TOGGLE D-RING or MDU: 72, the step will flash in BLUE and GREEN on the UI.

This means that there is no automatic proceed for the current step; it is something you will need to do manually. You will learn more about this later, but for now, manually press the CHECKMARK button for all these steps to proceed.

Anyways, press RUN to let the checklist guidance system help you set the remaining switches. Look for the blue guidance square to find the switches, and set the remaining switches. Press the CHECKMARK for all manual steps.
{{capsuleName}}, all systems reading OK. We are go for launch.
Another feature of Reentry is timescaling. You can use the Numeric Keys to set the time scale. 1 is Normal time, and sequential numbers are multiples of this.

Use the time scale to speed up time. The time scale will return to normal when a message is received, or before important stages. Timescaling is blocked during powered maneuvers such as ascent and reentry etc.
Press 4 to speed up time.
{{capsuleName}}, 60 seconds to launch.
{{profileName}}, use the [C]ommunications Menu to let Ground know we are ready for launch. When the circular buttons are visible on the COMMANDER'S SEAT, press the READY TO LAUNCH circular button.
30 seconds to launch. It's good practice to briefly look over the major things to verify things are ready for launch.
Ok, this is it.
Good luck!
Lift off!
We are having a lot of vibrations. Systems looking good. Monitoring instruments. Over.
Roger. 30 seconds.
{{g}} g's, cabin {{cabinPSI}} psi, I see Stage 1 fuel decreasing normally, fuel is go. Altitude increasing.
Roger. 60 seconds.
Staging feels good. Stage 2 ignited, red lights extuinguished. Stage 2 burning.
Roger.
{{g}} g's, cabin {{cabinPSI}} psi, I see Stage 2 fuel decreasing normally, fuel is go.

Ok, we are now using Stage 2 to ascend into the initial orbit. This will mostly focus on building orbital speed as we power slightly above the horizon. User the [V]iew Selector to look outside when you have time.
Roger.
Enjoy the view, I will monitor the systems.
{{g}} g's, cabin {{cabinPSI}} psi, I see Stage 2 fuel decreasing normally, fuel is go.
Roger. Prepare for SECO.
SECO!
Roger. Separate from Stage 2.
Roger. {{profileName}}, press the covered SEP SPCFT pushbutton to separate us from the Launch Vehicle.
Separating from the Launch Vehicle.
Separation complete
Roger.
Next, remove the fairings with the button above to uncover our scanners, radar and sensors.

Please take note of the red SCANNER light on the center pedestal. If this is ON, the scanners are not able to track Earth. This is normal for about 120 seconds after jettisoning the fairings. Don't perform any automaneuvers if this light is on.
Ok {{profileName}}, use the [M]ission Pad checklists to enable the OAMS system - this is the system used to enable attitude control (so you can rotate the craft). This is the ENABLE OAMS checklist.
Gemini can both change its orientation and alter its trajectory using the OAMS.
Good. Feel free to look around and get familiar with the cockpit for 2 minutes while I prepare the navigation.
{{capsuleName}}, we wish that you try the RATE COMMAND flight mode during the Orbit. Over.

Roger. {{profileName}}, use the RATE COMMAND MODE checklist (unless you have pressed something, this should already be correctly set up) to set the flight mode to manual rate command. In this mode, you can use [W] and [S] to pitch [A] and [D] to Yaw and [Q] and [E] to Roll. Give it a try! Then use time scale until the next instruction.

We are about to reach the African coast and Madagascar, and we are about to transition into the night side of Earth. Check out the sunset by looking in the retrograde direction if you wish. Then use time scale until the next instruction.

For your information, to modify the current orbital trajectory you need to use the translational thrusters. Use [H] to go forward, [N] for backwards, [J] to go left, [L] to go right, [I] to go up, and [K] to go down.

Due to the high altitude, you can't really notice translation unless you are docking or executing burns where visual cues or data on the computer shows you this. Then use time scale until the next instruction.

We are soon flying over Australia. The night lights from the major cities should easily be visible unless there are clouds. This also completes the mission. If you know the spacecraft, feel free to take it down through reentry! Good job today!

Title: The Titan
Description: The Gemini-Titan rocket is ready on the pad, where Commander Patrick and his crew will launch the first Gemini mission that will take the astronauts and the new spacecraft into orbit around Earth. One orbit is scheduled before returning back to Earth.
BriefingText:
BRIEFING

The Gemini spacecraft will launch into orbit using the Titan Launch Vehicle. The spacecraft will orbit Earth once before firing the retrograde engines to return back to Earth and splash down in the Atlantic.

The retrograde sequence will start at 1 hour and 31 minutes into the flight, just when passing over Texas. This will alter the orbital trajectory and reentry will happen just off the coast of Florida with a splashdown in the Atlantic Ocean.

The Mission will be completed when you are in orbit. You can quit the mission here and the Commander will perform the reentry. If you know what you are doing, you can continue the mission and perform the reentry yourself.

Good luck!
